  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q036",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "computer-architecture",
    "subtopic": "boot-process",
    "stem": "From what location are the 1st computer instructions available on boot up?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "ROM BIOS",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "CPU",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "boot.ini",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "CONFIG.SYS",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "At power-on RAM is empty, so the CPU fetches its very first instruction from the reset vector, which is mapped to firmware held in ROM BIOS. boot.ini and CONFIG.SYS are files on disk, and reading a disk already requires running code, so they cannot be first.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 1
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "cd61df8072d4e62f3b526d7e9d43dd612229eaba"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q037",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "troubleshooting",
    "stem": "What could cause a fixed disk error.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "No-CD installed",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "bad ram",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "slow processor",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Incorrect CMOS settings",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "'Fixed disk' means the hard disk. Legacy BIOS stores the drive type and geometry in CMOS, so if those settings are wrong or the CMOS battery has failed, POST cannot address the drive and reports a fixed disk error. Bad RAM or a slow processor produce entirely different symptoms.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 2
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "40338a7fa77657482b3c23d37bea7cb5b5461d18"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q038",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "pc-hardware",
    "stem": "Missing slot covers on a computer can cause?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "over heat",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "power surges",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "EMI.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "incomplete path for ESD",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Slot covers seal the case so the fans pull air along the intended path across the boards; with covers missing the airflow short-circuits and the machine overheats (and dust gets in). EMI is a defensible real-world second answer because the covers are part of the shield, but overheating is the keyed one.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 3
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "e995a7ced8db5ff136336a0e325a8add22658508"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q039",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "pc-hardware",
    "stem": "When installing PCI NICS you can check the IRQ availability by looking at",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "dip switches",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "CONFIG.SYS",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "jumper settings",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "motherboard BIOS",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "PCI cards are jumperless and configured by Plug and Play, so there are no dip switches or jumpers to read. IRQ assignment and availability are shown in the motherboard BIOS setup under PnP/PCI configuration. CONFIG.SYS is a DOS text file and tracks no interrupts.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "a8995cc5a49af39aa22afe894f8edc569b3735c2"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q040",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "network-devices",
    "stem": "With respect to a network interface card, the term 10/100 refers to",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "protocol speed",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "a fiber speed",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "megabits per seconds",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "minimum and maximum server speed",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "10/100 means the NIC negotiates either 10 Mbps or 100 Mbps Ethernet, so the numbers are megabits per second. It is a link speed on copper (10BASE-T / 100BASE-TX), not a fiber rate and not a property of the protocol.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "f3b1b78fb2ceea02dcc6109bc2a024295fb636f1"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q041",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "motherboard",
    "stem": "Which Motherboard form factor uses one 20 pin connector",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "ATX",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "AT",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "BABY AT",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "ATX introduced the single keyed 20-pin motherboard power connector. AT and Baby AT used two separate 6-pin connectors (P8 and P9) that could be swapped and plugged in backwards, which is why the ATX design replaced them.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 6
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "8c2cb549035a2321357ecf85de6619dedc159c48"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q042",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "disk-storage",
    "stem": "A hard disk is divided into tracks which are further subdivided into:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "clusters",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "sectors",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "vectors",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "heads",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of the above",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Each platter surface has concentric tracks, and every track is divided into sectors, the smallest physically addressable unit on the disk (classically 512 bytes). Clusters are the trap: they are groups of sectors defined by the file system, not a subdivision of the disk geometry.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
